package com.insurance.customer.dto;

import lombok.*;

import java.time.LocalDate;

@Getter
@Setter
@NoArgsConstructor
@AllArgsConstructor
public class CustomerRequestDTO {

    private String firstName;
    private String lastName;
    private String mobileNumber;
    private LocalDate dob;
    private String email;
    private String username;
    @JsonProperty(access = JsonProperty.Access.WRITE_ONLY)
    private String password;

    @JsonProperty(access = JsonProperty.Access.WRITE_ONLY)
    private String confirmPassword;
}

@JasonProperty(access = JasonProperty.Access.WRITE_ONLY)
* Instead of using @JasonIgnore in entity, we can use @JasonProperty in DTO
*access.WRITE_ONLY  --> which means we can't read, we can only write

Why we should not use @JasonIgnore in DTO:-
* Controller layer converts Object to JSON
*"Jackson" Library is responsible for it.
* @JasonIgnore --> Ignore Always (Read and Wright)
*Request is Mapped to DTO, not entity.
*Entity comes after service.
*So, we should use in Entity
*The better way is using @Jason Property.
